===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
{{Han compound|示|alt1=礻|t1=altar|豊|t2=ceremony|ls=psc|ls2=ic|c1=s|c2=p}} – performing rites at the altar.

Originally written {{zh-l|*豊}}, see there for more.

===Etymology===
{{unc|zh}}. {{zh-ref|Schuessler (2007)}} proposes that this is an old {{w|Mainland Southeast Asia linguistic area|areal}} etymon. Compare {{cog|bo|ཞེ་ས|t=respect, honor, deference}}, {{m|bo|རྗེ་བོ|t=lord, nobleman}}, {{m|bo|རྗེད|t=to honor; reverence}}; {{cog|mro|tr=ri|t=ritual}} is possibly borrowed from {{w|Austroasiatic languages|Austroasiatic}} (cf. {{cog|mnw|tr=rèh seh|t=to respect, to revere}}; Thin {{cog|kjg|tr=rɛh|t=to lift up}}; both from {{cog|mkh-pro|*reh||to raise up, to exalt}}).

